 treasurer, and to Sanabassar the governor of Judea. And he sent away all the vessels. Then the third, who had spoken of women and of truth, began to speak. O ye men, is not the king strong? Are not men strong that rule over sea and land? But above all things truth beareth away the victory. Wine is wicked, the king is wicked, women are wicked, all the children of men are wicked, and such are all their works; and there is no truth in them; in their unrighteousness also they shall perish. As for truth, it endureth, and is always strong; it liveth and conquereth for evermore. With her there is no accepting of persons or rewards; but she doeth the things that are just, and refraineth from all unjust and wicked things; and all men do well like of her works. Neither in her judgment is any unrighteousness; and she is the strength, kingdom, power, and majesty, of all ages. Blessed be the God of truth. And with that he held his peace. And all the people then shouted, and said, Great is truth, and mighty above all things. Then the king said unto him… And when these three had spoken, the king said unto them, What shall we do? And they said, We will write three things, and the king shall command that he whose writing shall be found the wisest, shall have great gifts and great honour from the king. One wrote, Wine is the strongest. The second wrote, The king is the strongest. The third wrote, Women are strongest, but above all things truth beareth away the victory. Then the king and the princes looked one upon another. Then the king said unto the third, What is the strongest thing of all? Then the third, who had spoken of women and of truth, began to speak… And the king and the princes and the captains looked one upon another… Then the king said unto them, Tell me now, what is the strongest thing of all? Then the third, who had spoken of women and of truth, began to speak… And when the king had spoken thus, he commanded that they should bring the three young men before him, that